    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<h3>Worked Solution</h3>

<p>
This question is based on interpreting a <strong>displacement–time graph</strong>.
</p>
<ul>
<li>The <strong>slope</strong> of a displacement–time graph tells you the velocity.</li>
<li>A <strong>horizontal line</strong> means the object is at rest.</li>
<li><strong>Total distance</strong> and <strong>displacement</strong> are not the same.</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h4>Part (a): Description of motion</h4>

<ul>
<li>
<strong>Segment A (0 to {@t1@} s):</strong><br>
The graph is a straight line with a <strong>positive slope</strong>, so the object moves with
<strong>constant positive velocity</strong>.
</li>

<li>
<strong>Segment B ({@t1@} to {@t2@} s):</strong><br>
The graph is <strong>horizontal</strong>, meaning the displacement does not change.
Therefore, the object is <strong>at rest</strong>.
</li>

<li>
<strong>Segment C ({@t2@} to {@t3@} s):</strong><br>
The graph is a straight line with a <strong>negative slope</strong>, so the object moves with
<strong>constant negative velocity</strong>, returning towards the starting point.
</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h4>Part (b): Velocity during segment A</h4>

<p>
Velocity is given by the slope of the displacement–time graph:
</p>

\[
v = \frac{\text{change in displacement}}{\text{change in time}}
= \frac{{@d1@}}{{@t1@}} = {@float(v_A)@}\ \text{m/s}.
\]

<hr>

<h4>Part (c): Stationary segment</h4>

<p>
The object is stationary when the graph is horizontal (zero slope).
This occurs during <strong>Segment B</strong>.
</p>

<hr>

<h4>Part (d): Total distance travelled</h4>

<p>
Total distance is the <strong>sum of all distances travelled</strong>, regardless of direction:
</p>

<ul>
<li>Distance travelled upward: {@d1@} m</li>
<li>Distance travelled downward: {@d1@} m</li>
</ul>

<p>
\[
\text{Total distance} = {@d1@} + {@d1@} = {@total_distance@}\ \text{m}.
\]
</p>

<hr>

<h4>Part (e): Average velocity</h4>

<p>
Average velocity is defined as:
</p>

\[
\text{Average velocity} = \frac{\text{total displacement}}{\text{total time}}.
\]

<p>
Since the object returns to its starting point, the total displacement is zero.
Therefore:
</p>

\[
\text{Average velocity} = 0\ \text{m/s}.
\]

<hr>]]></text>
